@Nomograph Mastering  As a result of this convo I hunted down Paul’s GS posts on this. Now, I’m going to have to learn about what floating point really means and what is a “mantissa”. The subject of his  knowledge is fascinating . 
quote :” If your mix is sounding bad the more stuff you put into it, it may be because the stuff itself is flawed, inappropriate and/or low quality processing. But it sure as hell isn't because of the precision of the system itself.” P. Frindle 

Dope

@oaklandmatt @spectrummasters I want y'all to gas me up more on these points. These ideas are beautiful. I feel this at a human level. I don't share your lack of concern, but want more evidence to fuel some hope. It seems to me much about the way information (music included) travels online from a systems view is misaligned with these values / ideals and generative AI / fake artists will just make it worse. I don't mean to highjack the convo either so can move this to a thread if that makes sense.
"I think a part of being a human is that we intrinsically move towards the authentic and not the imitation"
"This part of it I'm not actually worried about. Human beings continue to want to connect to other human beings, and music is still fundamentally a way to connect one person to another."

Split EQ can help after de-verbing to further tame some tonal mud across different frequencies if it’s all plagued with reverb.

That said, an entire mix like that is rough, I don’t envy that task.

@jordanmcleod_io is onto something though, if they can send stems that’d be far better.
